        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1988-01-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1988-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="318"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d318">
                <head>318. Paper Prepared in the National Security Council<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d318fn1">Source: Reagan Library, African Affairs Directorate, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Records, Subject File, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>—Policy. No classification marking.
                            <persName corresp="#p_SPS_2">Schott Stevens</persName> sent the paper to
                            <persName corresp="#p_CWA_1">Cockell</persName>, Cohen, <persName
                            corresp="#p_DSI_1">Danzansky</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_DRW_1"
                            >Dean</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_EFW_1">Ermarth</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_FAB_1">Alison Fortier</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KDB_1">Barry Kelly</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KJA_1"
                            >James Kelly</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_LRE_1"
                        >Linhard</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_ORB_1">Oakley</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_RPW_1">Rodman</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_RCN_1">Nicholas Rostow</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJS_1">Soranzo</persName> under a January 26 covering
                        memorandum, writing: “<persName corresp="#p_NJD_1">John
                            Negroponte</persName> has requested that I circulate the attached ‘1988
                        Overview,’ which <persName corresp="#p_GTC_1">Tom Griscom</persName> has
                        prepared as a month-by month sketch of major themes he will be seeking to
                        develop during the remainder of the President’s term in office.” <persName
                            corresp="#p_SPS_2">Schott Stevens</persName> noted that <persName
                            corresp="#p_NJD_1">Negroponte</persName> welcomed comments on the paper.
                        (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-editorial-annotation"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1988-01-26">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">1988 Overview</p>
                <p>General Theme: Preparing for the Challenges of Tomorrow <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>this focuses on the future;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>provides the framework for legislative actions;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>describes specific goals for the President but also sets out a course
                            for his successor;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>states what must be done to meet these goals;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>provides the opportunity to look back and then look forward.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Objective:</p>
                <p>To provide a forum to advance and institutionalize the Reagan agenda; to lay down
                    the framework for a political victory by the Republican Party in 1988.</p>
                <p>Leading Issues: <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>war/peace (arms control; East/West relations)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>quality education</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>combating illicit drugs</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>government spending (budget/deficits/process)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>All of these issues are consistent with the Reagan agenda and can be a major part
                    of the 1988 agenda. While there is the opportunity to score legislative
                    victories in 1988, there is also the opportunity to sketch what the future
                    should be and where it might go. An extremely important point: this agenda is
                    relevant, consistent, optimistic.</p>
                <pb facs="1527" n="1458" xml:id="pg_1458"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">1988 Monthly Agenda</p>
                <p>January:</p>
                <p>Theme: looking ahead/setting the agenda <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>State of the Union Address<note n="2" xml:id="d318fn2">The President
                                delivered his State of the Union address on January 25. For the text
                                of the address, see <hi rend="italic">Public Papers: Reagan,
                                    1988–1989</hi>, Book I, pp. 84–90. The text of the President’s
                                1988 legislative and administrative message, entitled “A Union of
                                Individuals,” is ibid., pp. 91–121.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>quality education/jobs</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>dealing with illicit drugs</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss>/arms control/growth of <rs
                                corresp="recOWsM3ry8STSsK3" type="topic">democracy</rs>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>economy/process reform</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>February:</p>
                <p>Theme: legislative action/a winner <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_Contras_1">Contras</gloss>
                            <note n="3" xml:id="d318fn3">Reference is to congressional action
                                regarding the administration’s $36 million support package for the
                                    <gloss target="#t_Contras_1">Contras</gloss>. The House of
                                Representatives was scheduled to vote on the proposal on February
                                3.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>budget/two-year agreement/process</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Supreme Court confirmation</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>North American Accord scene-setter (Mexico)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>March:</p>
                <p>Theme: working with the <rs corresp="recwBHUin5Stz6rON" type="topic"
                        >Alliance</rs>/national security <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>national defense/national security</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <rs corresp="recQl77x6qBlGdnAY" type="topic">conventional weapons</rs>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>arms control/arms reduction</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>April:</p>
                <p>Theme: North American relations/world relations <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Canada Free <rs corresp="recZJL0JHE1yyaPgZ" type="topic">Trade
                                Agreement</rs>
                            <note n="4" xml:id="d318fn4">See <ref target="#d316fn2">footnote 2,
                                    Document 316</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>North American Accord (Canada/US/Mexico)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Central America (possible)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> ratification</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <pb facs="1528" n="1459" xml:id="pg_1459"/>
                <p>May:</p>
                <p>Theme: the role of the Peacemaker <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Moscow summit<note n="5" xml:id="d318fn5">Scheduled to take place May
                                29–June 2. The memoranda of conversation are printed in <ref
                                    target="frus1981-88v06#d156">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. VI,
                                    Soviet Union, October 1986–January 1989, Documents
                                    156</ref>–<ref target="frus1981-88v06#d163">163</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>arms control/arms reduction</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <rs corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2" type="topic">human rights</rs>/<rs
                                corresp="rec7XCpI38AIhVpLJ" type="topic">regional
                            issues</rs>/bilateral issues</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>June:</p>
                <p>Theme: forging domestic/international economic policy <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Economic summit in Canada<note n="6" xml:id="d318fn6">Scheduled to
                                take place June 19–21.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <rs corresp="recprkqi9dIeoip4s" type="topic">debt</rs> strategy</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>budget/<rs corresp="recWWVFNMUXe07vmZ" type="topic">deficit</rs>
                            reduction/process reform</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>monetary policy<note n="7" xml:id="d318fn7">An unknown hand placed a
                                brace in the left-hand margin, bracketing the May and June points
                                and wrote: “we could make Babangida ‘fit’ either of these. APR.”
                                Reference is to General Ibrahim Babangida of Nigeria.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>July:</p>
                <p>Theme: developing new economic markets <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Pacific Rim to support market-oriented growth</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Democratic National Convention occurs<note n="8" xml:id="d318fn8"
                                >Scheduled to take place in Atlanta at The Omni Coliseum, July
                                18–21.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>August:</p>
                <p>Theme: recognizing our American Institutions/setting political agenda <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>culmination of bicentennial of <rs corresp="reckLQalsfRO3AT43"
                                type="topic">Constitution</rs>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>citing 100th Congress/role/changes/improvements</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Republican National Convention occurs<note n="9" xml:id="d318fn9"
                                >Scheduled to take place in New Orleans at the Superdome, August
                                15–18.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>September/October/November/December:</p>
                <p>Theme: role of the presidency/political debate <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>American values</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>the future (education/technology)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>managing <rs corresp="rectqbCKMJaN5yPfG" type="topic">foreign
                                policy</rs>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>the institution of government/relationships</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>economic and budget policies</item>
                        <pb facs="1529" n="1460" xml:id="pg_1460"/>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Farewell Address: Vision of America (late December-early January)<note
                                n="10" xml:id="d318fn10">The President’s January 11, 1989, farewell
                                address to the nation is printed as Document 335.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">Major National Speeches: <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>State of the Union (January)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_Contras_1">Contras</gloss> (February)<note n="11"
                                xml:id="d318fn11">On February 2, the President delivered an address
                                to the nation regarding aid to the Nicaraguan Democratic Resistance
                                and the $36 million aid package (see <ref target="#d318fn3">footnote
                                    3</ref>, above). The address is printed in <hi rend="italic"
                                    >Public Papers: Reagan, 1988–1989</hi>, Book I, pp.
                                162–167.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss> (March)<note n="12"
                                xml:id="d318fn12">The President discussed the March 2–3 <gloss
                                    target="#t_NATO_1">NATO</gloss> summit meeting in Brussels in
                                his March 5 radio address; for the text, see ibid., pp.
                                294–295.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Moscow Summit (May)<note n="13" xml:id="d318fn13">The President’s May
                                31 remarks, made before students and faculty at Moscow State
                                University, are printed as Document 326.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Economic Summit (June)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Republican National Convention (August)<note n="14" xml:id="d318fn14"
                                >The President offered remarks at the convention on August 15. For
                                the text of his remarks, see <hi rend="italic">Public Papers:
                                    Reagan, 1988–1989</hi>, Book II, pp. 1080–1086.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Institutional speeches (September/October/December)</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Farewell Address (January 1989)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
